I liked UltraTerm III for the C128.  It's greatest shortcoming was no ANSI
mode.  For ANSI boards, I used DesTerm.  UltraTerm worked fine on CBM and
ASCII boards.

It also has a large capture buffer which can be edited, saved, loaded into,
sent over the modem, etc.  60 Kb if I remember correctly.

I used a PC for word processing.  Whenever I wanted a large CBM text file, I
would use the PC word processor to create it.  Then save as ASCII, transfer
it to the good ole C128 and convert it to PETSCII.  Just made an important
discovery.  The substitution of ole for old may have originated as a typo
that slipped by a proofreader.    ;-)

Little Red Reader on the C128 made it easy to combine transferring the file
and translating it into a single step.  As another side note on translation
methods, UltraTerm could also be used to translate either way between ASCII
and PETSCII.  Just load a file, translate it (a quick operation as
translation was done in memory), then save it.

For a small CBM text file I would use a text editor such as Ed Parry's Goofed
128 to create it on the CBM side of things.
--
